Project description¶

Sweet Lift Taxi company has collected historical data on taxi orders at airports. To attract more drivers during peak hours, we need to predict the amount of taxi orders for the next hour. Build a model for such a prediction.

The RMSE metric on the test set should not be more than 48.

Project instructions¶

  1. Download the data and resample it by one hour.
  2. Analyze the data.
  3. Train different models with different hyperparameters. The test sample should be 10% of the initial dataset.
  4. Test the data using the test sample and provide a conclusion.

Data description¶

The data is stored in file taxi.csv. The number of orders is in the 'num_orders' column.

def get_precent_of_na_df(df,num):
    df_nulls = pd.DataFrame(df.isna().sum(),columns=['Missing Values'])
    df_nulls['Percent of Nulls %'] = round(df_nulls['Missing Values'] / df.shape[0],num) *100
    df_nulls = df_nulls.sort_values("Percent of Nulls %",ascending=False)
    return df_nulls

def Explore(df):
    df = df
    print(df.head())
    print("Number of duplicated rows",df.duplicated().sum())
    print("Data shape",df.shape)
    print('Columns with nulls:')
    display(get_precent_of_na_df(df,4))
    display(df.info())
    display(df.describe())
    print("Number of duplicated rows")
    display(df.duplicated().sum())
    temp_raw_data=df.copy()
    fig = plt.figure(figsize = (7,10))
    ax = fig.gca()
    temp_raw_data.hist(ax = ax)
    fig = ax.get_figure()

Data exploration conclusion¶

The data is simple. Two columns, one fiture and one target. We have a right sided tail distribution, with most of the time low passengers (10-20) and few times there are picks of over 20.

No null values or missing data. Date column should be datetime type.

2. Analysis¶

First analysis¶

  1. We can see that in total the trend is going up and more people are using taxis in general.
  2. But, the use of taxis depends on the hour of the day, there is a seasonality on the use deppending on the hour of the day.
  3. The variance between hours also get higher, so it is more important in this days to find the picks.
  4. The minimum of passengeres per hour had not change during the last month, and even is getting higher than the beggining, although the variaty grew.
  5. Some hours there are not even one passenger.
  6. We have almost a right sided tail distribution, a bit normalized, but still the median is lower than the mean.
  7. Most of the time average (85) amount of passengers (55-105) and few times there are picks of over 180.
  8. A group of hours have picks between 180-300 PPH (passengers per hour)
  9. The min and max of the time is March-August 2018

Final analysis¶

  1. We can see that in total the trend is going up specialy in the last month, and more people are using taxis.
  2. But, as we said before, the use of taxis depends on the hour of the day. The picks are before work day and after work day, and after mid-night when people go back home from parties.
  3. There is a high seasonality, the number of PPH repeats every day deppending on the hour of the day.
  4. The residuals per day may seem high, but it has only two big picks in the last month, and almost no negative picks. Thus, every day may seem the same as last day, with a little upping trend.
  5. Some hours there are not even one passenger.
  6. Most of the time on last month, the average was during the 130 PPH, the interval of quatinties is of 90-160 PPH and few times there are picks of over 250 and less than 50.
  7. The min and max of PPH is 13-462, meaning that no 0 hours, but very high picks.

def make_features(data, max_lag, rolling_mean_size):
    data['year'] = data.index.year
    data['month'] = data.index.month
    data['day'] = data.index.day
    data['dayofweek'] = data.index.dayofweek

    for lag in range(1, max_lag + 1):
        data['lag_{}'.format(lag)] = data['num_orders'].shift(lag)

    data['rolling_mean'] = data['num_orders'].shift().rolling(rolling_mean_size).mean()

df_daytime = df.copy()
make_features(df_daytime, 4, 1)

train, test = train_test_split(df_daytime, shuffle=False, test_size=0.2)
train = train.dropna()
features_1 = train.drop(columns=['num_orders'], axis=1)
target_1 = train['num_orders']
features_test = test.drop(columns=['num_orders'], axis=1)
target_test = test['num_orders']

features_train, features_valid, target_train, target_valid = train_test_split(
    features_1, target_1, shuffle=False, test_size=0.2)

print('Size of features to train:', features_train.shape)
print('Size of features to validate:', features_valid.shape)
print('Size of features to test:', features_test.shape)

In [10]:
def print_model_RMSE(mod):
    model = mod
    model.fit(features_train,target_train)
    predicted_valid = model.predict(features_valid)
    rmse_training = mean_squared_error(target_train, model.predict(features_train))**0.5
    rmse_valid = mean_squared_error(target_valid, predicted_valid)**0.5

    print("RMSE for the training set:", rmse_training)
    print("RMSE for the valid set: ", rmse_valid)

def print_model_RMSE_test(mod):
    model = mod
    model.fit(features_1,target_1)
    predicted_test = model.predict(features_test)
    rmse_training = mean_squared_error(target_1, model.predict(features_1))**0.5
    rmse_test = mean_squared_error(target_test, predicted_test)**0.5

    print("RMSE for the training set:", rmse_training)
    print("RMSE for the test set: ", rmse_test)

Conclusion¶

The best model, and aso fast one, is LinearRegression. Its RMSE is the lowest, and makes it the model with the best result.

Not only from the model, but also from the analysis, we saw that the trend of PPH is going up, thah before and after work is the picks, and also after midnight.

The model predicts the seasonability and the trend can be noticed. Still the average of the prediction is lower than the last month average, meanining that the model misses the trend.
